{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487300","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487300"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:05:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:05:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"313"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582571"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:47:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:47:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"313"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"313","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/313"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.01,0.76,0.01,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"313"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90836"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"313","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/313"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"313"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74899"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"324"},{"type":"tags","id":"1239"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12333"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31138"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90836"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old man presents with testicular pain. This has been ongoing since a kick to the groin during a soccer match two days ago. The pain has not abated with regular analgesia and ice packs applied to the groin. On examination, the left testis is swollen, tender on palpation, with a palpably thickened cord. There is no overlying erythema of the skin. The testis does not transilluminate. The cremasteric reflex is present bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the next most appropriate investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Surgical exploration","Testicular biopsy","Ultrasound","Urinalysis","Radionuclide studies"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFor any acute, painful scrotal problem, testicular torsion must be ruled out before other conditions are considered. The history and examination findings detract from torsion, as normally this is usually acute in onset, with severe unilateral pain with overlying erythema and swelling. Often the testis is in horizontal lie, with an absent cremasteric reflex and negative Phren\u2019s sign. Most patients with torsion seek help within hours of onset - and not the 48+ hours in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in the given scenario is trauma and potential haematoma. Surgical exploration is the first line investigation in suspected torsion, but in this case an \u003Cstrong\u003Eultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E should be performed first. This examination will be able to define the position and structure of the testis, its blood flow (reduced on doppler studies) as well as the presence of a haematoma or fluid collection (secondary to trauma). It can also help diagnose epididymitis (increased blood flow), the other main differential for a painful testis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBiopsy is never done, as this can seed a potential cancer throughout the scrotum. Urinalysis is indicated for a suspected infection, which does not fit this clinical picture. Radionucleotide studies can provide a definitive diagnosis of torsion however this is not first line and rarely needed as it most often is diagnosed clinically.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ultrasound should be the first line investigation for suspected testicular haematoma, when the degree of urgency does not warrant immediate surgical exploration."],"references":["Bourke MM, Silverberg JZ. Acute Scrotal Emergencies. Emerg Med Clin N Am 2019 37:593-610."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74899"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"313"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74899","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74899"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T17:02:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T17:02:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"313"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90836"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable 